etymologies: late 19th century; earliest use found in Journal of the Chemical Society. From pyrazole + -ine, after German Pyrazolin

definitions: Each of three heterocyclic compounds having the formula C₃ H₆ N₂ which are dihydro derivatives of pyrazole; specifically 2-pyrazoline; a substituted derivative of such a compound.

notes.text: There are three possible isomeric forms of pyrazoline, of which only one (more fully "2-pyrazoline"), CH₂CH₂CHNNH, a colourless, basic liquid, has been prepared.
